I'm confused. Why would the return value be set on the request object? This is undocumented and seems like bad practice. The recommended way is to use res.locals. Though if you set a variable on the response you might as well just res.json(ret) as it's not much of an improvement. Also, not sure if you're required to call next() in this scenario.
My intent was to decouple the service layer from the HTTP layer. Why don't we just return ret; and then in server.js:
